Â Â  . â MrÂ President, it is clear that safety is essential.
Railway safety is good in most cases at the moment, and it is imperative that it remain good, at least as good as it is now.
I extend my thanks to many of my fellow Members, therefore, for their valuable contribution to the debate on safety, and also to many people from the railway community, who have made a fair few suggestions, improved the texts, pointed out difficulties and so on.
If a European rail transport market is established, there must of course also be a European safety system.
We are creating that by means of this Directive: Common Safety Targets, a method for achieving those targets, and a safety authority in each Member State that uses a common method to give licences to all the parties concerned.
Following the Council common position, we held a number of discussions, and there followed mediation by the Commission with representatives of the Council.
